<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">

<p><b>Land Rover</b> is a car brand that specialises in <a href="/wiki/Four-wheel-drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Four-wheel-drive">four-wheel-drive</a> vehicles, owned by British <a href="/wiki/Multinational_corporation" title="Multinational corporation">multinational</a> <a href="/wiki/Automaker" class="mw-redirect" title="Automaker">car manufacturer</a> <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Land_Rover" title="Jaguar Land Rover">Jaguar Land Rover</a>, which has been owned by India's <a href="/wiki/Tata_Motors" title="Tata Motors">Tata Motors</a> since 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> The Land Rover is regarded as a British icon, and was granted a Royal Warrant by King <a href="/wiki/George_VI" title="George VI">George VI</a> in 1951.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Land Rover name was originally used by the <a href="/wiki/Rover_Company" title="Rover Company">Rover Company</a> for the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series" title="Land Rover Series">Land Rover Series</a>, launched in 1948. It developed into a brand encompassing a range of four-wheel-drive models, including the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Defender</a>, <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Discovery" title="Land Rover Discovery">Discovery</a>, <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Freelander" title="Land Rover Freelander">Freelander</a>, <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover" title="Range Rover">Range Rover</a>, <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Sport" title="Range Rover Sport">Range Rover Sport</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Evoque" title="Range Rover Evoque">Range Rover Evoque</a>. Land Rovers are currently assembled in the company's <a href="/wiki/Halewood_Body_%26_Assembly" title="Halewood Body &amp; Assembly">Halewood</a> and <a href="/wiki/Solihull_plant" title="Solihull plant">Solihull</a> plants, with research and development taking place at the <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Land_Rover_Gaydon_Centre" title="Jaguar Land Rover Gaydon Centre">Gaydon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Whitley_plant" title="Whitley plant">Whitley</a> engineering centres. Land Rover sold 194,000 vehicles worldwide in 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></p>
<p>In September 2013, Jaguar Land Rover announced plans to open a 100 million <a href="/wiki/Pound_sterling" title="Pound sterling">GBP</a> (160 million <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">USD</a>) research and development centre in the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Warwick" title="University of Warwick">University of Warwick</a>, Coventry to create a next generation of vehicle technologies. The carmaker said around 1,000 academics and engineers would work there and that construction would start in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></p>

<p>The design for the original Land Rover vehicle was started in 1947 by <a href="/wiki/Maurice_Wilks" title="Maurice Wilks">Maurice Wilks</a>, chief designer at the <a href="/wiki/Rover_Company" title="Rover Company">Rover Company</a>, on his farm in <a href="/wiki/Newborough,_Anglesey" title="Newborough, Anglesey">Newborough, Anglesey</a>, working in conjunction with his brother <a href="/wiki/Spencer_Wilks" title="Spencer Wilks">Spencer</a> who was the managing director of Rover.<sup id="cite_ref-dt_20080328_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dt_20080328-10">[10]</a></sup> The design may have been influenced by the <a href="/wiki/Bantam_GP" class="mw-redirect" title="Bantam GP">Jeep</a><sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> and the prototype, later nicknamed <a href="/wiki/Centre_Steer" title="Centre Steer">Centre Steer</a>, was built on a Jeep chassis and axles.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> The early choice of colour was dictated by <a href="/wiki/Military_surplus" title="Military surplus">military surplus</a> supplies of aircraft cockpit paint, so early vehicles only came in various shades of light green; all models until recently feature sturdy box section ladder-frame chassis. Early vehicles like the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series#Series_I" title="Land Rover Series">Series I</a> were field-tested at Long Bennington and designed to be field-serviced.</p>
<p>Land Rover as a company has existed since 1978. Prior to this, it was a product line of the <a href="/wiki/Rover_Company" title="Rover Company">Rover Company</a> which was subsequently absorbed into the Rover-Triumph division of the <a href="/wiki/British_Leyland_Motor_Corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="British Leyland Motor Corporation">British Leyland Motor Corporation</a> (BL) following <a href="/wiki/Leyland_Motor_Corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="Leyland Motor Corporation">Leyland Motor Corporation</a>’s takeover of Rover in 1967. The ongoing commercial success of the original Land Rover series models, and latterly the Range Rover in the 1970s in the midst of BL's well-documented business troubles prompted the establishment of a separate Land Rover company but still under the BL umbrella, remaining part of the subsequent <a href="/wiki/Rover_Group" title="Rover Group">Rover Group</a> in 1988, under the ownership of <a href="/wiki/British_Aerospace" title="British Aerospace">British Aerospace</a> after the remains of British Leyland were broken up and privatised. In 1994 Rover Group plc was acquired by <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a>. In 2000, Rover Group was broken up by BMW and Land Rover was sold to <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a>, becoming part of its <a href="/wiki/Premier_Automotive_Group" title="Premier Automotive Group">Premier Automotive Group</a>. In 2006 Ford purchased the Rover brand from BMW for around £6 million.</p>
<p>In 2008, <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a> sold <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Cars" title="Jaguar Cars">Jaguar</a> and Land Rover to Tata Motors. Included in the deal were the rights to three other British brands: Jaguar's own <a href="/wiki/Daimler_Company" title="Daimler Company">Daimler marque</a>, as well as two dormant brands <a href="/wiki/Lanchester_Motor_Company" title="Lanchester Motor Company">Lanchester</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rover_Company" title="Rover Company">Rover</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a> and Ford had previously retained ownership of the Rover brand to protect the integrity of the Land Rover brand, with which 'Rover' might be confused in the US 4x4 market; the Rover brand was originally used under licence by <a href="/wiki/MG_Rover" class="mw-redirect" title="MG Rover">MG Rover</a> until it collapsed in 2005, at which point it was re-acquired by the then Ford Motor Company owned Land Rover Limited. This sale also included the dormant Rover brand.<sup id="cite_ref-ford_20080326_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ford_20080326-14">[14]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-r_20080602_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-r_20080602-16">[16]</a></sup> As of August 2012<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Land_Rover&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, most Land Rovers in production are powered by Ford engines.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT-454888_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-454888-17">[17]</a></sup> Under the terms of the acquisition, Tata has the right to buy engines from Ford until 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-BloombergNews-618828_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BloombergNews-618828-18">[18]</a></sup> In 2011, Tata confirmed plans that it is investing $559 million to build an engine assembly plant in the British West Midlands. However, it was only stated that the plant will produce four-cylinder engines. The eight-cylinder engines used in Land Rovers were not mentioned.<sup id="cite_ref-C4WDefault-3608800_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-C4WDefault-3608800-19">[19]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Timeline">Timeline</span></h3>
<ul>
<li>1947: Rover's chief designer Maurice Wilks and his associates create a prototype using Jeep chassis and components<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup></li>
<li>1948: The first Land Rover was officially launched 30 April 1948, at the Amsterdam Motor Show</li>
<li>1958: <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series_II" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover Series II">Series II</a> launched</li>
<li>1961: <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series_IIa" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover Series IIa">Series IIA</a> began production</li>
<li>1967: Rover becomes part of <a href="/wiki/Leyland_Motors_Ltd" class="mw-redirect" title="Leyland Motors Ltd">Leyland Motors Ltd</a>, later <a href="/wiki/British_Leyland" title="British Leyland">British Leyland</a> (BL) as Rover Triumph</li>
<li>1970: Introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Classic" title="Range Rover Classic">Range Rover</a></li>
<li>1971: <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series_III" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover Series III">Series III</a> launched</li>
<li>1974: Land Rover abandons US market, facing competitive pressure from Japanese 4x4 brands <sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup></li>
<li>1975: BL collapses and is nationalised, publication of the <a href="/wiki/Ryder_Report_(British_Leyland)" title="Ryder Report (British Leyland)">Ryder Report</a> recommends that Land Rover be split from Rover and be treated as a separate company within BL and becomes part of the new commercial vehicle division called the Land Rover Leyland Group</li>
<li>1976: One-millionth Land Rover leaves the production line</li>
<li>1978: Land Rover Limited formed as a separate subsidiary of British Leyland<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup></li>
<li>1980: Rover car production ends at Solihull with the transfer of SD1 production to Cowley, Oxford; Solihull is now exclusively for Land Rover manufacture. 5-door Range Rover introduced.</li>
<li>1983: <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Land Rover 90 (Ninety)/110 (One-Ten)/127</a> (renamed Defender in 1990) introduced</li>
<li>1986: BL plc becomes Rover Group plc; <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Llama" title="Land Rover Llama">Project Llama</a> started</li>
<li>1987: Range Rover is finally introduced to the US market, following many years of demand being filled by <a href="/wiki/Grey_import_vehicle" title="Grey import vehicle">grey market sales</a> <sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup></li>
<li>1988: Rover Group is privatised and becomes part of <a href="/wiki/British_Aerospace" title="British Aerospace">British Aerospace</a>, and is now known simply as <a href="/wiki/MG_Rover" class="mw-redirect" title="MG Rover">Rover</a></li>
<li>1989: Introduction of <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Discovery" title="Land Rover Discovery">Discovery</a></li>
<li>1994: Rover Group is taken over by <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a>. Introduction of second-generation Range Rover. (The original Range Rover was continued under the name 'Range Rover Classic' until 1995)</li>
<li>1997: Land Rover introduces the Special Edition Discovery XD with AA yellow paint, subdued wheels, SD type roof racks, and a few other off-road upgrades directly from the factory. Produced only for the North American market, the Special Vehicles Division of Land Rover created only 250 of these bright yellow SUVs.</li>
<li>1997: Introduction of <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Freelander" title="Land Rover Freelander">Freelander</a></li>
<li>1998: Introduction of second generation of Discovery</li>
<li>2000: BMW breaks up the Rover Group and sells Land Rover to <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford</a> for £1.8 billion<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup></li>
<li>2002: Introduction of third-generation <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover" title="Range Rover">Range Rover</a></li>
<li>2004: Introduction of third-generation <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Discovery" title="Land Rover Discovery">Discovery/LR3</a></li>
<li>2005: Introduction of <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Sport" title="Range Rover Sport">Range Rover Sport</a></li>
<li>2005: Adoption of <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_AJ-V8_engine" title="Jaguar AJ-V8 engine">Jaguar AJ-V8 engine</a> to replace the <a href="/wiki/BMW_M62" title="BMW M62">BMW M62</a> <a href="/wiki/V8_engine" title="V8 engine">V8</a> in the Range Rover</li>
<li>2005: Land Rover 'founder' <a href="/wiki/Rover_Company" title="Rover Company">Rover</a>, collapses under the ownership of MG Rover Group</li>
<li>2006: Announcement of a new 2.4-litre diesel engine, 6-speed gearbox, dash and forward-facing rear seats for Defender. Introduction of second generation of Freelander (Freelander 2). Ford acquires the Rover trademark from BMW, who previously licensed its use to MG Rover Group</li>
<li>8 May 2007: 4,000,000th Land Rover rolls off the production line, a Discovery 3 (LR3), donated to The <a href="/wiki/Born_Free_Foundation" title="Born Free Foundation">Born Free Foundation</a></li>
<li>12 June 2007: Announcement from the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a> that it plans to sell Land Rover and also <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Cars" title="Jaguar Cars">Jaguar Cars</a></li>
<li>August 2007: Tata Motors and <a href="/wiki/Mahindra_and_Mahindra" class="mw-redirect" title="Mahindra and Mahindra">Mahindra and Mahindra</a> as well as financial sponsors <a href="/wiki/Cerberus_Capital_Management" title="Cerberus Capital Management">Cerberus Capital Management</a>, <a href="/wiki/TPG_Capital" title="TPG Capital">TPG Capital</a> and <a href="/wiki/Apollo_Global_Management" title="Apollo Global Management">Apollo Global Management</a> expressed their interest in purchasing <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Cars" title="Jaguar Cars">Jaguar Cars</a> and Land Rover from the Ford Motor Company.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup></li>
<li>26 March 2008: Ford agreed to sell their <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Land_Rover" title="Jaguar Land Rover">Jaguar Land Rover</a> operations to Tata Motors.<sup id="cite_ref-ford_20080326_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ford_20080326-14">[14]</a></sup></li>
<li>2 June 2008: Tata Motors finalised their purchase of Jaguar and Land Rover from Ford.<sup id="cite_ref-r_20080602_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-r_20080602-16">[16]</a></sup></li>
<li>2010: Introduction of fourth-generation <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Discovery" title="Land Rover Discovery">Discovery/LR4</a></li>
<li>2011: The <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Evoque" title="Range Rover Evoque">Range Rover Evoque</a> introduced</li>
<li>2012: <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_(L405)" title="Range Rover (L405)">Fourth-generation Range Rover</a> was exhibited at the <a href="/wiki/2012_Paris_Motor_Show" title="2012 Paris Motor Show">2012 Paris Motor Show</a></li>
<li>2014: The New Discovery Range was unveiled at the 2014 New York Motor Show <sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Manufacturing">Manufacturing</span></h2>
<p>Land Rovers were manufactured primarily at the <a href="/wiki/Solihull_plant" title="Solihull plant">Solihull plant</a>, near <a href="/wiki/Birmingham" title="Birmingham">Birmingham</a>, but production of the Freelander was moved to the <a href="/wiki/Halewood_Body_%26_Assembly" title="Halewood Body &amp; Assembly">Halewood Body &amp; Assembly</a> plant near <a href="/wiki/Liverpool" title="Liverpool">Liverpool</a>, a former Ford car plant. The Freelander is also assembled in <a href="/wiki/Knock-down_kit" title="Knock-down kit">knock-down kit</a> (CKD) form at Land Rover's facility in <a href="/wiki/Pune" title="Pune">Pune</a>, India.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup></p>
<p>Defender models are assembled under licence in several locations worldwide, including Spain (<a href="/wiki/Santana_Motors" class="mw-redirect" title="Santana Motors">Santana Motors</a>), Iran (Pazhan <a href="/wiki/Morattab" title="Morattab">Morattab</a>), Brazil (<a href="/wiki/Karmann" title="Karmann">Karmann</a>), and Turkey (<a href="/wiki/Otokar" title="Otokar">Otokar</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> The former BL/Rover Group technical centre at Gaydon in Warwickshire is one of the JLR group's design centres, and the former Jaguar Cars head office in Whitley is now the group head office and another group design facility.</p>
<p>In May 2010, Tata Motors announced that it plans to build Land Rover and Jaguar models in <a href="/wiki/Mainland_China" title="Mainland China">Mainland China</a> (<a href="/wiki/PRC" class="mw-redirect" title="PRC">PRC</a>) as the company seeks to cut costs and expand sales.<sup id="cite_ref-tatachina_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tatachina-30">[30]</a></sup></p>
<p>In late 2012, the automaker announced a <a href="/wiki/Joint_venture" title="Joint venture">joint venture</a> for Jaguars and Land Rovers to be built in China, now the world's biggest car-market. The agreement is with <a href="/wiki/Chery" title="Chery">Chery</a>, China's sixth largest auto manufacturer, and calls for a new Chinese factory in <a href="/wiki/Changshu" title="Changshu">Changshu</a> to build vehicles starting in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> Trial production at the facility began in April 2014, with a potential capacity of 130,000 vehicles annually.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> The first production model by the <a href="/wiki/Chery_Jaguar_Land_Rover" title="Chery Jaguar Land Rover">Chery Jaguar Land Rover</a> venture is the Evoque, with other models planned that also include modifications, such as longer wheelbases, to satisfy Chinese market demand.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Concepts">Concepts</span></h2>
<p><a href="/wiki/Range_Stormer" class="mw-redirect" title="Range Stormer">Range Stormer</a> – Land Rover's first <a href="/wiki/Concept_car" title="Concept car">concept vehicle</a>, unveiled at the 2004 <a href="/wiki/North_American_International_Auto_Show" title="North American International Auto Show">North American International Auto Show</a>, later became the <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Sport" title="Range Rover Sport">Range Rover Sport</a>.(Gritzinger, 2004).</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_LRX" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover LRX">Land Rover LRX</a> – Land Rover's second concept vehicle, first unveiled at the <a href="/wiki/Detroit_Auto_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="Detroit Auto Show">2008 Detroit Auto Show</a>. Originally a vehicle with ERAD technology, the production version did not include this. The car was then launched in 2011 as the <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Evoque" title="Range Rover Evoque">Range Rover Evoque</a>, and was the first Range Rover branded product to be offered with front wheel drive, and no low ratio transfer box.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_DC100" title="Land Rover DC100">Land Rover DC100</a> – Land Rover's third concept vehicle, first unveiled at the <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Auto_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="Frankfurt Auto Show">2011 Frankfurt Auto Show</a>, designed to be a replacement for the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Land Rover Defender</a>, though it is unlikely that the Defender's replacement will be exactly the same as the DC100 concept.</p>
<p>Land Rover Discovery Vision Concept – Land Rover's fourth concept vehicle, first unveiled at the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Auto_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Auto Show">2014</a>, was designed to be a replacement for the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Discovery" title="Land Rover Discovery">Land Rover Discovery</a>, This concept features Transparent Bonnet, Suicide doors, and Laser assisted lamps (there is a very little chance this will be included in any future production vehicles).</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Military">Military</span></h3>
<p>Models developed for the UK <a href="/wiki/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)" title="Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)">Ministry of Defence</a> (MoD) include:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_101_Forward_Control" title="Land Rover 101 Forward Control">101 Forward Control</a> – also known as the "Land Rover One Tonne FC"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_1/2_ton_Lightweight" title="Land Rover 1/2 ton Lightweight">1/2 ton Lightweight</a> – airportable military short-wheelbase from the Series 2a</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Wolf" title="Land Rover Wolf">Land Rover Wolf</a> – an uprated Military Defender</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Snatch_Land_Rover" title="Snatch Land Rover">Snatch Land Rover</a> – Land Rover with composite armoured body in UK Armed Forces Service</li>
<li>109 Series IIa and III ambulance (body by <a href="/wiki/Marshall_Aerospace" class="mw-redirect" title="Marshall Aerospace">Marshalls of Cambridge</a>)</li>
<li>Range Rover '6x6' Fire Appliance (conversion by Carmichael and Sons of Worcester) for RAF airfield use</li>
<li>130 Defender ambulance</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Llama" title="Land Rover Llama">'Llama'</a> prototypes for 101 replacement.</li>
</ul>
<p>Models developed for the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Army" title="Australian Army">Australian Army</a></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Perentie" title="Land Rover Perentie">Land Rover Perentie</a> 4X4 and 6X6</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Engines">Engines</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_engines" title="Land Rover engines">Land Rover engines</a></div>
<p>During the history of the Land Rover many different engines have been fitted:</p>
<ul>
<li>The inlet-over-exhaust petrol engines ("semi side-valve"), in both four- and six-cylinder variants, which were used for the very first Land Rovers in 1948, and which had their origins in pre-war Rover cars. Displacement of the first models was 1,600&#160;cc.</li>
<li>The four-cylinder overhead-valve engines, both petrol and diesel, which first appeared (in diesel form) in 1957, near the end of Series One production, and evolved over the years to the 300 TDi turbodiesel, which remains in production today for some overseas markets.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Buick" title="Buick">Buick</a>-sourced all aluminium <a href="/wiki/Rover_V8" class="mw-redirect" title="Rover V8">Rover V8</a> engine.</li>
<li>1,997 cc Petrol, inlet-over-exhaust: Series I engine, carried over for the first few months of Series II production.</li>
<li>2,052 cc Diesel, overhead-valve: Land Rover's first diesel engine, and one of the first small high-speed diesels produced in the UK. It appeared in 1957, and was used in Series II production until 1961. Looks almost identical to the later 2,286 cc engine, but many internal differences. It produced 51&#160;bhp (38&#160;kW).</li>
<li>2,286 cc Petrol, overhead-valve, three-bearing crank:</li>
<li>2,286 cc Diesel, overhead-valve, three-bearing crank: Appeared in 1961 alongside the redesigned 2,286 cc petrol engine at the start of Series IIA production, and shared its cylinder block and some other components. It produced 62&#160;bhp (46&#160;kW).</li>
<li>2,625 cc Petrol, inlet-over-exhaust: Borrowed from the Rover saloon range, in response to demands from mid-1960s Land Rover users for more power and torque.</li>
<li>2,286 cc petrol/diesel, overhead-valve type 11J: five-bearing crank: In 1980, Land Rover finally did something about the crank failures which had plagued its four-cylinder engines for 22 years.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2009)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> These engines lasted beyond the end of Series III production and into the first couple of years of the new Ninety and One Ten ranges.</li>
<li>3,258 cc V8 Petrol: The ex-Buick all alloy V8 engine appeared in the Range Rover right from the start of production in 1970, but did not make its way into the company's utility vehicles until 1979.</li>
<li>2,495 cc petrol, overhead valve: The final development of Land Rover's ohv petrol 'four', with hardened valve seats which allow running on unleaded (or LPG).</li>
<li>2,495 cc diesel, overhead valve, type 12J: Land Rover reworked the old 'two and a quarter' diesel for the 1980s. The injection pump was driven off a toothed belt at the front of the engine (together with the camshaft), a change compared with the older diesels.</li>
<li>2,495 cc turbodiesel, overhead valve, type 19J</li>
<li>2,495 cc turbodiesel, overhead valve, 200TDi and 300TDi: Used in the Defender and Discovery from 1990. The cylinder block was similar to the previous engine, although strengthened but the cylinder head was all-new and a direct injection fuel system was used.</li>
<li>2,495 cc turbodiesel, five-cylinder, TD5: An all-new engine for the second generation Discovery, and the Defender featuring electronic control of the fuel injection system, '<a href="/wiki/Drive_by_wire" title="Drive by wire">drive by wire</a>' throttle, and other refinements</li>
<li>The original Freelander models were available with various <a href="/wiki/Rover_K_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="Rover K engine">Rover K-series engines</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Electric_vehicles">Electric vehicles</span></h2>
<table class="plainlinks metadata ambox mbox-small-left ambox-content" role="presentation">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><a href="/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg" class="image"><img alt="[icon]" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png" width="20" height="14" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/30px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="44" data-file-height="31" /></a></td>
<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span"><b>This section needs expansion</b>. <small>You can help by <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Land_Rover&amp;action=edit&amp;section=">adding to it</a>.</small> <small><i>(March 2009)</i></small></span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Integrated Electric Rear Axle Drive (ERAD) technology, dubbed e-terrain technology,<sup id="cite_ref-worldcarfans.com_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-worldcarfans.com-34">[34]</a></sup> will allow the vehicle to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/move_off" class="extiw" title="wikt:move off">move off</a> without starting the engine as well as supplying extra power over tough terrain.<sup id="cite_ref-worldcarfans.com_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-worldcarfans.com-34">[34]</a></sup> Land Rover's Diesel ERAD Hybrid was developed as part of a multimillion-pound project supported by the UK Government's <a href="/wiki/Energy_Saving_Trust" title="Energy Saving Trust">Energy Saving Trust</a>, under the <a href="/wiki/Low_carbon" class="mw-redirect" title="Low carbon">low carbon</a> research and development programme. ERAD programme is one of a broad range of sustainability-focused engineering programmes that Land Rover is pursuing, brought together by the company under the collective name "e TERRAIN Technologies".<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup></p>
<p>Land Rover presented at the 2008 <a href="/wiki/London_Motor_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="London Motor Show">London Motor Show</a> its new ERAD <a href="/wiki/Diesel-electric_transmission" title="Diesel-electric transmission">diesel-electric</a> hybrid in a pair of <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Freelander" title="Land Rover Freelander">Freelander 2</a> (LR2) prototypes. The new hybrid system is being designed as a scalable and modular system that could be applied across a variety of Land Rover models and powertrains.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup></p>
<p>Land Rover unveiled the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_LRX" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover LRX">LRX hybrid concept</a> at the <a href="/w/index.php?title=2008_North_American_International_Auto_Show&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="2008 North American International Auto Show (page does not exist)">2008 North American International Auto Show</a> in Detroit, for it to be going into production.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> An ERAD will enable the car to run on electric power at speeds below 20&#160;mph (32&#160;km/h).<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<p>In September 2011, the <a href="/wiki/Range_Rover_Evoque" title="Range Rover Evoque">Range Rover Evoque</a> was launched, though it was based on the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_LRX" class="mw-redirect" title="Land Rover LRX">LRX hybrid concept</a> presented at the <a href="/w/index.php?title=2008_North_American_Auto_Show&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="2008 North American Auto Show (page does not exist)">2008 North American Auto Show</a>, it did not include the ERAD system, included in the original concept.</p>
<p>In February 2013, Land Rover unveiled<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> at the 83rd <a href="/wiki/Geneva_Motor_Show" title="Geneva Motor Show">Geneva Motor Show</a> an <a href="/wiki/All_Terrain_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="All Terrain Vehicle">All-Terrain</a> <a href="/wiki/Electric_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Electric Vehicle">Electric</a> <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Defender</a> that produces zero emissions. The electric vehicle was developed for research purposes following successful trials of the Defender-based electric vehicle, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Land_Rover_Leopard_1&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Land Rover Leopard 1 (page does not exist)">Leopard 1</a>. The vehicle is capable of producing 70<a href="/wiki/KW" class="mw-redirect" title="KW">kW</a> and 330<a href="/wiki/Newton_metre" title="Newton metre">Nm</a> of <a href="/wiki/Torque" title="Torque">torque</a> and has a range of 80 kilometres or in low speed off-road use it can last for up to eight hours before recharging.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Abilities">Abilities</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Land-Rover.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Land-Rover.JPG/220px-Land-Rover.JPG" width="220" height="182" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Land-Rover.JPG/330px-Land-Rover.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Land-Rover.JPG/440px-Land-Rover.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2209" data-file-height="1826" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Land-Rover.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Land-Rovers at <a href="/wiki/AgQuip" title="AgQuip">AgQuip</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gunnedah,_New_South_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="Gunnedah, New South Wales">Gunnedah</a>, Australia</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Power_take-off" title="Power take-off">Power take-off</a> (PTO) was integral to the Land Rover concept from 1948, enabling farm machinery and many other items to be run with the vehicle stationary. Maurice Wilks' original instruction was "...to have power take-offs everywhere!" The 1949 report by British National Institute of Agricultural Engineering and Scottish Machinery Testing Station contained this description: "the power take-off is driven through a <a href="/wiki/Hardy_Spicer" title="Hardy Spicer">Hardy Spicer</a> propeller shaft from the main gearbox output and two interchangeable pinions giving two ratios. The PTO gearbox casing is bolted to the rear chassis cross-member and an 8 by 8 inches (200&#160;mm ×&#160;200&#160;mm) belt pulley driven from the PTO shaft through two bevel gears can be bolted to the PTO gearbox casing." PTOs remained regular options on Series I, II and III Land Rovers up to the demise of the Series Land Rover in 1985. An agricultural PTO on a Defender is possible as a special order.</p>
<p>Land Rovers (the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Series/Defender models</a>) are available in a variety of body styles, from a simple canvas-topped pick-up truck to a twelve-seat fully trimmed <a href="/wiki/Station_wagon" title="Station wagon">station wagon</a>. Both Land Rover and out-of-house contractors have offered conversions and adaptations to the basic vehicle, such as <a href="/wiki/Fire_engine" title="Fire engine">fire engines</a>, <a href="/wiki/Excavator" title="Excavator">excavators</a>, <a href="/wiki/Elevating_platform" class="mw-redirect" title="Elevating platform">'cherry picker' hydraulic platforms</a>, ambulances, <a href="/wiki/Snowplough" class="mw-redirect" title="Snowplough">snowploughs</a>, and six-wheel-drive versions, as well as one-off special builds including <a href="/wiki/Amphibious_vehicle" title="Amphibious vehicle">amphibious</a> Land Rovers and vehicles fitted with tracks instead of wheels.</p>

Land Rovers on parade with the <a href="/wiki/Italian_Army" title="Italian Army">Italian Army</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marina_Militare" class="mw-redirect" title="Marina Militare">Navy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aeronautica_Militare" class="mw-redirect" title="Aeronautica Militare">Air Force</a>, June 2007</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Various Land Rover models have been used in a military capacity, most notably by the <a href="/wiki/British_Army" title="British Army">British Army</a> and <a href="/wiki/Australian_Army" title="Australian Army">Australian Army</a>. Modifications may include military "blackout" lights, heavy-duty suspension, uprated brakes, 24&#160;volt electrics, convoy lights, electronic suppression of the ignition system, blackout curtains and mounts for special equipment and small arms. Dedicated military models have been produced such as the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_101_Forward_Control" title="Land Rover 101 Forward Control">101 Forward Control</a> and the air-portable <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_1/2_ton_Lightweight" title="Land Rover 1/2 ton Lightweight">1/2&#160;ton Lightweight</a>. Military uses include light utility vehicle; communications platform; weapon platform for <a href="/wiki/Recoilless_rifle" title="Recoilless rifle">recoilless rifles</a>, <a href="/wiki/Anti-tank" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-tank">Anti-tank</a> (e.g. <a href="/wiki/BGM-71_TOW" title="BGM-71 TOW">TOW</a> or <a href="/wiki/M40_recoilless_rifle" title="M40 recoilless rifle">M40 recoilless rifle</a>) / <a href="/wiki/Surface-to-air_missile" title="Surface-to-air missile">Surface-to-Air</a> Guided Weapons or machine guns; ambulances and workshops. The Discovery has also been used in small numbers, mostly as liaison vehicles.</p>
<p>Two models that have been designed for military use from the ground up are the 101 Forward Control from the early 1970s and the Lightweight or Airportable from the late 1960s. The latter was intended to be transported under a helicopter. The <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force_Mountain_Rescue_Service_(United_Kingdom)" class="mw-redirect" title="Royal Air Force Mountain Rescue Service (United Kingdom)">Royal Air Force Mountain Rescue Service</a> (RAFMRS) teams were early users in the late 1950s and early 1960s, and their convoys of Land Rovers and larger military trucks are a sight often seen in the mountain areas of the United Kingdom. Originally RAFMRS Land Rovers had blue bodies and bright yellow tops, to be better seen from above. In 1981, the colour scheme was changed to green with yellow stripes. More recently, vehicles have been painted white, and are issued with fittings similar to civilian UK <a href="/wiki/Mountain_Rescue" class="mw-redirect" title="Mountain Rescue">Mountain Rescue</a> teams.</p>
<p>An adaptation of Land Rovers to military purposes is the "Pink Panther" models. Approximately 100 Series IIA models were adapted to <a href="/wiki/Reconnaissance" title="Reconnaissance">reconnaissance</a> use by British special operations forces the <a href="/wiki/Special_Air_Service" title="Special Air Service">SAS</a>. For desert use they were often painted pink, hence the name. The vehicles were fitted with among other gear a <a href="/wiki/Solar_compass" title="Solar compass">sun compass</a>, machine guns, larger fuel tanks and smoke dischargers. Similar adaptations were later made to Series IIIs and 90/110/Defenders.<sup id="cite_ref-LMS_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LMS-41">[41]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Australian Army adapted the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series" title="Land Rover Series">Land Rover Series</a> 2 into the <a href="/wiki/Long_Range_Patrol_Vehicle" title="Long Range Patrol Vehicle">Long Range Patrol Vehicle</a> for use by the <a href="/wiki/Special_Air_Service_Regiment_(Australia)" class="mw-redirect" title="Special Air Service Regiment (Australia)">Special Air Service Regiment</a> and as an anti-tank "gunbuggy" fitted with an <a href="/wiki/M40_recoilless_rifle" title="M40 recoilless rifle">M40 recoilless rifle</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/75th_Ranger_Regiment" class="mw-redirect" title="75th Ranger Regiment">75th Ranger Regiment</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Army" title="United States Army">United States Army</a> also adapted twelve versions of the Land Rover that were officially designated the <a href="/wiki/Ranger_Special_Operations_Vehicle" title="Ranger Special Operations Vehicle">Ranger Special Operations Vehicle</a>.</p>
<p>Series and Defender models have also been armoured. The most widespread of these is the <a href="/wiki/Shorland_armoured_car" title="Shorland armoured car">Shorts Shorland</a>, built by <a href="/wiki/Shorts_Brothers" class="mw-redirect" title="Shorts Brothers">Shorts Brothers</a> of <a href="/wiki/Belfast" title="Belfast">Belfast</a>. The first of these were delivered in 1965 to the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Ulster_Constabulary" title="Royal Ulster Constabulary">Royal Ulster Constabulary</a>, the Northern Ireland police force. They were originally 109-inch (2,800&#160;mm) wheelbase models with an armoured body and a turret from the <a href="/wiki/Ferret_armoured_car" title="Ferret armoured car">Ferret armoured car</a>. By 1990, there had been more than 1,000 produced.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> In the 1970s, a more conventional armoured Land Rover was built for the Royal Ulster Constabulary in Wales called the Hotspur. The <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Tangi" title="Land Rover Tangi">Land Rover Tangi</a> was built by the Royal Ulster Constabulary's own vehicle engineering team during the 1990s. The British Army has used various armoured Land Rovers, first in Northern Ireland but also in more recent campaigns. They first added protective panels to Series General Service vehicles (the Vehicle Protection Kit (VPK)). Later they procured the Glover Webb APV and finally the Courtaulds (later NP Aerospace) Composite Armoured Vehicle, commonly known as <a href="/wiki/SNATCH_Land_Rover" class="mw-redirect" title="SNATCH Land Rover">Snatch</a>. These were originally based on heavy-duty V8 110 chassis but some have recently been re-mounted on new chassis from <a href="/wiki/Otokar" title="Otokar">Otokar</a> of Turkey and fitted with diesel engines and air-conditioning for Iraq. Although these now have more in common with the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Wolf" title="Land Rover Wolf">'Wolf'</a> (Defender XD) Land Rovers that many mistakenly confuse them with, the Snatch and the Wolf are different vehicles.</p>
<p>The most radical conversion of a Land Rover for military purposes was the Centaur <a href="/wiki/Half-track" title="Half-track">half-track</a>. It was based on a Series III with a V8 engine and a shortened belt drive from the <a href="/wiki/Alvis_Scorpion" class="mw-redirect" title="Alvis Scorpion">Alvis Scorpion</a> light <a href="/wiki/Tank" title="Tank">tank</a>. A small number was manufactured, and they were used by Ghana, among others.</p>
<p>The Land Rover is used by military forces throughout the world. The current generation of Land Rover used by British Army, the Snatch 2, have upgraded and strengthened chassis and suspension compared to civilian-specification vehicles. There is also the Land Rover WMIK (weapon mounted installation kit) used by British Army. The WMIK consists of a driver, a raised gun, usually a Browning heavy machine gun or a grenade machine gun, this used for ground support, and a GPMG (general-purpose machine gunner) located next to the driver, this used for vehicle protection.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Competitive_use">Competitive use</span></h3>
<p>Highly modified Land Rovers have competed in the <a href="/wiki/Dakar_Rally" title="Dakar Rally">Dakar Rally</a> and won the <a href="/wiki/Macmillan_4x4_UK_Challenge" title="Macmillan 4x4 UK Challenge">Macmillan 4x4 UK Challenge</a> almost every year, as well as having been the vehicle used for the <a href="/wiki/Camel_Trophy" title="Camel Trophy">Camel Trophy</a>. Now, Land Rover has its own <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_G4_Challenge" title="Land Rover G4 Challenge">G4 challenge</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Driver_training">Driver training</span></h2>
<p>Land Rover Experience was established in 1990, and consists of a network of centres throughout the world, set up to help customers get the most out of their vehicles' on and off-road capability. The flagship centres are Land Rover's bases at Solihull, Eastnor, Gaydon and Halewood. Courses offered include off-road driving, winching and trailer handling, along with a variety of corporate and individual 'Adventure Days'. The factory centres at Solihull and Halewood have manufacturing tours, while Gaydon has an engineering tour.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Safety">Safety</span></h2>
<p>Model-by-model road accident statistics from the UK <a href="/wiki/Department_for_Transport" title="Department for Transport">Department for Transport</a> show that the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Defender" title="Land Rover Defender">Land Rover Defender</a> is one of the safest cars on British roads as measured by chance of death in two-car injury accidents.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> The figures, which were based on data collected by police forces following accidents between 2000 and 2004 in Great Britain, showed that Defender drivers had a 1% chance of being killed or seriously injured and a 33% chance of sustaining any kind of injury. Other four-wheel-drive vehicles scored equally highly, and collectively these vehicles were much safer for their passengers than those in other classes such as passenger cars and MPVs. These figures reflect the fact that drivers of large mass vehicles are likely to be safer, often at the expense of other drivers if they collide with smaller cars.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Clubs">Clubs</span></h2>
<p>The original Land Rover Owners Club was set up by the Rover Company in 1954. The company published the Land Rover Owners Club Review magazine for members from 1957 to 1968 when the club became the Rover Owners Association. This original association fell away when the company merged with British Leyland.</p>
<p>There are many Land Rover clubs throughout the UK and internationally. Land Rover clubs break down into a number of groups of varying interests.</p>
<p>Single Marque Clubs – Bring together owners of a specific model or series of vehicle such as the Land Rover Series One Club,<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup> or the Discovery Owners Club.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> Clubs based on ownership of earlier series vehicles tend to attract the purists amongst Land Rover owners whose interests often relate to restoration of their vehicles to their original condition.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2008)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>. Single marque clubs have a global membership.</p>
<p>Special Vehicle Clubs – At various times Land Rover have produced vehicles for specific events or on a specific theme, most notable are the <a href="/wiki/Camel_Trophy" title="Camel Trophy">Camel Trophy</a> and G4 Challenge vehicles which have been sold on to the general public, and a range of Defenders that were loosely based on the custom vehicles produced for the Tomb Raider motion picture.</p>
<p>Regional Clubs in the UK break down into two groups, competitive and non-competitive. The non-competitive clubs activities generally relate to social events, off road driving or <a href="/wiki/Green_laning" class="mw-redirect" title="Green laning">green laning</a> on un-surfaced public highways or 'pay and play' days at off road centres. Competitive clubs are a phenomenon almost exclusively found within the UK, who as well as the non-competitive activities detailed above run competitive events such as Tyro, Road Taxed Vehicle (RTV) and Cross Country Vehicle (CCV) trials, winch and recovery challenges or speed events such as Competitive Safaries. All UK competitive events are run within the framework of rules created by the <a href="/wiki/Motor_Sports_Association" title="Motor Sports Association">Motor Sports Association</a> (MSA) with further vehicle specific rules applied by the host club or association. Outside of the UK regional clubs are independent and mostly non-competitive.</p>
<p>A number of clubs are affiliated to the Association of Land Rover Clubs (ALRC),<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup> formerly known as the Association of Rover Clubs (ARC) the association applies its own vehicle regulations to all of its member clubs who have the opportunity to compete together at regional events and an annual national event with vehicles approved to the same standard. In recent years some non-competitive clubs have dropped their affiliation fifth ALRC. Few clubs outside of the UK are affiliated with ALRC.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup> Other than ALRC and the short lived Association of North American Rover Clubs (ANARC), which was created 1998 to celebrate Land Rover's 50th anniversary and disbanded in 2001, other groups of Land Rover clubs have affiliated with each other.</p>
<p>Land Rover owners were also early adopters of virtual clubs that are entirely based online. Bill Caloccia <sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> created the original Land Rover Owner<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup> email list (LRO) as single marque offshoot of the British Cars email list in May 1990.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> Bill later created email lists in the mid 1990s for Range Rovers (RRO) and various regions (e.g., UK-LRO, AU-LRO, ZA-LRO, EU-LRO, IT-LRO, NL-LRO). In California members of the LRO list created mendo_recce in 1995.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup> LRO, UK-LRO, ZA-LRO and mendo_recce are still active email lists in 2014. As the web became popular forums web forums (e.g., Muddy Oval, Guns and Rovers, Defender Source, Land Rover Addict) and groups existing only in Facebook or other social media sites have been created and are popular communication methods.</p>
<p>In 2005, under Ford ownership, Land Rover became more interested in the club environment. An internal club was formed, The Land Rover Club,<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup> exclusive to employees of Ford's <a href="/wiki/Premier_Automotive_Group" title="Premier Automotive Group">Premier Automotive Group</a> (Now exclusive to the new 'Jaguar – Land Rover' group since the brand moved away from the Ford stable). Also, an agreement was generated to allow other clubs to use the Land Rover green oval logo under licence. In 2006, the Bedfordshire, Hertfordshire and Cambridgeshire club were the pilot licensees for the new agreement, who now benefit from a reciprocal arrangement where their own logo is trade marked<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup> and owned by Land Rover and they can refer to themselves as a 'Land Rover Approved Club'.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Brand_extensions">Brand extensions</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Bicycles">Bicycles</span></h3>
<p>In 1995, Land Rover endorsed the production of a hand-made bicycle using its logo. The bicycle, called the Land Rover APB and manufactured by <a href="/wiki/Pashley_Cycles" title="Pashley Cycles">Pashley Cycles</a> of Stratford-upon-Avon,<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup> was the collapsible version of Pashley Cycles' <a href="/wiki/Moulton_Bicycle" title="Moulton Bicycle">Moulton</a> APB (All Purpose Bicycle) model, with leading link front suspension and adjustable damping and stroke. Two more models immediately followed: the Land Rover XCB V-20, aimed primarily at younger riders (children); and the Land Rover XCB D-26, also available as the M26 with hydraulic rim brakes, front suspension and suspension seat pillar.</p>
<p>In June 2004, Land Rover released a comprehensive 25 model range of bicycles. The three main ranges are the "Defender", the "Discovery", and the "Freelander", each with different attributes. The "Discovery" is an all-rounder bicycle suited to a variety of terrains, "Defender" is most suited to rugged <a href="/wiki/Terrain" title="Terrain">terrain</a> and off road pursuits, whereas the "Freelander" is designed for an urban lifestyle. All bikes are made from lightweight aluminium.</p>
<p>In 2010 the range was relaunched in conjunction with British manufacturer 2x2.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Coffee">Coffee</span></h3>
<p>Land Rover has had its name associated with coffee since 2005, when the Land Rover Coffee company was established.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Pushchairs">Pushchairs</span></h3>
<p>Land Rover gave UK <a href="/wiki/Pushchair#Modern_designs" class="mw-redirect" title="Pushchair">pram</a> company Pegasus a licence to produce a three-wheeler range of Land Rover ATP <a href="/wiki/Pushchair#Modern_designs" class="mw-redirect" title="Pushchair">pushchairs</a>. The design reflected the heritage of the marque, with a light metal frame with canvas seating, held together with push-studs and tough simple parts like brakes and hinges. They could be collapsed completely flat, with wheels removed in seconds. The basic frame could be adapted with modules to allow a baby to lie flat or a bubble windscreen to completely enclose the child. The frame also came in long or short-handled versions, and could be repaired with home tools. The design was simple, light, and rugged and able to travel in all terrains (hence the ATP for all-terrain pushchair.) It came in three military looking colours: a light blue, a sand colour and olive drab. Production was discontinued in 2002.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Similar_vehicles">Similar vehicles</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Santana_Motor" title="Santana Motor">Santana Motor</a> Spanish licensed producer of modified Land Rovers
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iveco_Massif" title="Iveco Massif">Iveco Massif</a> Italian variant of Santana Anibal (produced jointly with Iveco, essentially a rebadged and branded PS-10) – rebadged and restyled version of the Santana PS-10. In 2010, the sales of the Iveco Massif were not as expected and Iveco decided to stop the agreement with Santana.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Morattab" title="Morattab">Morattab</a>, an <a href="/wiki/SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="SUV">SUV</a> manufacturer based in <a href="/wiki/Tehran" title="Tehran">Tehran</a>, Iran, has produced the <b>Herour</b>, a clone of the <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series" title="Land Rover Series">Series</a>, since 1962. The currently produced models are versions of the "Series IV" made by <a href="/wiki/Santana_Motor" title="Santana Motor">Santana Motor</a> of <a href="/wiki/Spain" title="Spain">Spain</a> until the early 1990s, when the production tooling and design were sold to Morattab and shipped to <a href="/wiki/Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a>. As such unlicensed Morattab clones differ significantly from the final <a href="/wiki/Land_Rover_Series#Series_III" title="Land Rover Series">Series III</a> built by Land Rover in the United Kingdom. For example, Series IV models have parabolic <a href="/wiki/Leaf_spring" title="Leaf spring">leaf springs</a>, one-piece <a href="/wiki/Windscreen" class="mw-redirect" title="Windscreen">windscreens</a> and fully fitted interiors. Morattab also fits locally built 1.8-litre 4-cylinder petrol engines derived from <a href="/wiki/Nissan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a> instead of the 2.25-litre 4-cylinder or 3.3-litre 6-cylinder engines fitted to the Santana Series IV.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bush_Ranger_(car)" title="Bush Ranger (car)">Bush Ranger</a> (also known as Bush Rangie) is an Australian permanent 4WD buggy based on a scrapped Range Rover or Discovery.</li>
</ul>
